<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUFFINGTON MAILS ADS THAT FEINSTEIN CALLS DECEPTIVE; POLITICS: BROCHURES STRESS 
HIS FAMILY LIFE AND ATTACK SENATOR. SHE CITES USE OF MILITARY PHOTO AS 
QUESTIONABLE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES RAINEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With California's airwaves already awash with his record-setting television 
advertising campaign, U.S. Senate candidate Mike Huffington now is mailing an 
unprecedented deluge of glossy literature to voters across the state. 
</P>
<P>
 Millions of Republican and Democratic households in California are expected to 
receive two full-color mailers in the final days of the campaign, defying the 
traditional wisdom that statewide offices are beyond the reach of expensive 
mail campaigns, professional campaign experts said. 
</P>
<P>
 Sen. Dianne Feinstein's campaign says the mailers are deliberately deceptive. 
Spokesmen note, for example, that prominently displayed pictures of a man 
resembling Huffington in a military uniform might suggest that Huffington has a 
military record, even though he has never served in the military. 
</P>
<P>
 Huffington campaign officials declined to discuss the extent of their mail 
effort against Feinstein, but campaign reports indicate that, even before the 
bulk of the literature was sent, the Republican congressman had bought enough 
postage for nearly 3 million mailers. That would dwarf any previous direct-mail 
efforts in the state, according to political consultants interviewed by The 
Times. And much more is on the way, predicted several professionals who 
specialize in campaign mailers. 
</P>
<P>
 "Mike Huffington has a big checkbook and he is not afraid to crack it open," 
said Ray McNally, a Republican consultant who worked for the challenger when he 
ran for his House seat. "If you have the funds to do it you would be crazy not 
to, because there are people you won't reach on television." 
</P>
<P>
 The two principal mailers in the effort -- one a Huffington biography and the 
other a piece attacking Feinstein as a greedy, special-interest politician -- 
have been criticized by the senator's campaign staff as deceptive. 
</P>
<P>
 One of the most striking, and potentially misleading, images is found in the 
challenger's eight-page "California Report." It is a photograph of a handsome 
young Huffington in full-dress Navy uniform. Only a small print caption near 
the bottom of the page tells the reader that the picture is of a different 
Huffington -- the candidate's father, Roy Huffington. 
</P>
<P>
 The candidate never was in the military, although he was old enough to serve 
in the Vietnam War. The candidate has said poor eyesight kept him out of the 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
 "They are attempting to have the casual reader believe that Huffington was in 
the military. There is no doubt about it," said Harvey Englander, a political 
consultant who works for both Republicans and Democrats. "I have never seen 
such a large picture in a political piece of a father who is not prominent 
himself." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Feinstein campaign manager Kam Kuwata: "He did less military service than 
Dan Quayle, if that's possible." 
</P>
<P>
 But the Huffington campaign defended the pictures. "He is from a family that 
he is very proud of," said Jennifer Grossman, Huffington's spokeswoman. "There 
are no secret codes or conspiracies in these pictures. They are there, 
literally, in black and white." 
</P>
<P>
 The biographical mailer is designed to bolster Huffington's image, after a 
campaign that has focused on attacking his opponent, several campaign 
professionals said. The brochure describes the challenger's education, business 
career and family life. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Most of all, it seems intent on overcoming charges that Huffington, a Texas 
native, moved to California only to pursue his political ambitions. The 
"California Report" title is repeated on each page of the brochure, which also 
features pictures of Huffington and wife Arianna in front of a California flag 
and running along the beach. 
</P>
<P>
 A second mailer delivers a withering attack on "The Feinstein Family 
Business," which it says is characterized by "greed and special interest 
politics." On the cover of the mailer, a picture of Feinstein smiles out from a 
collage that includes stacks of $100 bills and newspaper clippings about 
investigations of her husband's business activities. Inside, a grainy 
black-and-white photo shows Feinstein as she purportedly "puts the arm on 
lobbyists at a Washington, D.C., fund-raiser." 
</P>
<P>
 The overall impression of the mailer is that Feinstein and her husband, 
merchant banker Richard C. Blum, have used her career in elective office to 
help build their personal fortune of $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, Blum was already a wealthy financier when he married Feinstein in 
1980. A recent review by The Times found that, in two years as a senator, 
Feinstein has supported several positions that benefited her husband. She also 
has taken other stands that hurt his economic interests. 
</P>
<P>
 Feinstein has never been accused of violating the Senate's ethics rules, which 
permit her to vote on bills that affect Blum's finances, as long as the 
legislation is not designed specifically with that intent. 
</P>
<P>
 Several of the specific claims in the Huffington mailer also could be 
misleading. The mailer: 
</P>
<P>
 * Dubs Feinstein "the $6-million woman." The moniker refers to the amount of 
money she received from political action committees "who want or need favors 
from the federal government," the brochure says. The $6-million figure accounts 
for PAC donations for six years, according to the Feinstein campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 A Times analysis recently found that in the current campaign, Feinstein has 
relied more on small contributions than on special-interest money. With 17% of 
her money from PACs, she receives less of that money than the typical Senate 
winner in 1992, when PACs accounted for 27% of donations. 
</P>
<P>
 * Reports that Feinstein voted against a Senate pay cut, a true statement. It 
adds that the Senate raised salaries in 1992 by 30%, but Feinstein was not a 
senator at that time and so did not vote on the raise. 
</P>
<P>
 * Says that Feinstein voted against banning or limiting contributions from 
political action committees. Feinstein said that she supported the effort to 
control PAC donations and that her vote was recorded incorrectly. She asked 
that the Congressional Record be corrected. 
</P>
<P>
 Huffington spokesman Grossman said the mailer is meant to reinforce months of 
anti-Feinstein advertisements. "We are trying to show a philosophical thread 
that runs through this," Grossman said. "One candidate believes in more 
government solutions, and one candidate believes the government we have is part 
of the problem." 
</P>
<P>
 A third Huffington mailer in wide distribution is addressed from Mike 
Reynolds, the citizen sponsor of the "three strikes" criminal sentencing 
proposition on Tuesday's ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 In the first-person letter, Reynolds describes Feinstein as soft on crime 
because she voted to confirm a judge to the federal appellate court. 
</P>
<P>
 Feinstein has responded by noting that the judge in question confirmed more 
death penalty cases than she overturned and that even Florida Republican Sen. 
Connie Mack was among those who voted to confirm her. 
</P>
<P>
 The wave of advertising may have more impact because it will go virtually 
unchallenged by Feinstein, some experts said. The incumbent's campaign does not 
plan to send any mailers, although it will benefit from state Democratic Party 
literature being delivered on behalf of several candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 "On these mailers and other kinds of things, we just don't have the dough to 
do it," Kuwata said. "Of course I'm concerned about it. But the basic message 
and best way to communicate is through news events and (television) 
commercials." 
</P>
<P>
 In the current campaign, only gubernatorial candidate Kathleen Brown will 
mount a mailing effort that even approaches Huffington's. Brown plans to mail 
up to 1.4 million copies of her 64-page economic plan. It is "one of the 
largest direct-mail efforts in California political history," said Brown 
spokesman John Whitehurst. 
</P>
<P>
 But veteran Republican political consultant Allan Hoffenblum said he expects 
that Huffington will make the Brown effort seem paltry. Hoffenblum predicted 
that Huffington's camp may send 2 million or more of each of his mailers. 
</P>
<P>
 Campaign experts in California generally believe that the state is too large 
and the expense too great to launch anything but narrowly targeted mailers. 
Television is deemed to deliver much more impact per dollar. 
</P>
<P>
 But Huffington's campaign fund of more than $27 million has made many of the 
old rules of political campaigning expendable. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Huffington campaign is throwing everything they have at the voters, 
including the kitchen sink," Englander said. "All the consultants I have talked 
to are crying because they are not getting all the fees and commissions from 
this stuff." 
</P>
<P>
 Huffington's spokeswoman said the massive mailing effort should help refute 
claims that the candidate is trying to run his campaign through television. 
"This is a campaign run on ideas," Grossman said. "This is not a 30-second 
sound-bite candidate. This is somebody who has a vision and an agenda for this 
state which is best laid out in pieces such as these." 
</P>
<P>
 DISPUTE OVER HIRING: Huffington ad uses unverified story to attack Feinstein. 
A3 
</P>
<P>
 RELATED STORIES: A29 
</P>
