</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Antitrust Powers Expanded: President Clinton signed a bill this week 
permitting federal antitrust agencies to work with their foreign counterparts 
to protect American consumers and businesses from price fixing and other 
anti-competitive practices.The new law lets the Justice Department and the 
Federal Trade Commission enter into agreements with foreign agencies to 
exchange investigative information about companies and people in their 
jurisdictions. "Until now, U.S. antitrust enforcement agencies have often found 
vital evidence to be out of reach abroad," Clinton said in a statement. He said 
the new law will lower prices for American consumers and help the United States 
enforce its antitrust laws against foreign and international firms 
participating in the U.S. market. 
</P>
